-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Determine the units digit of 1² + 2² + … + 9² and show it equals 5. 2. [Key Idea] Work modulo 10: either add the individual squares’ residues or use the closed-form formula n(n + 1)(2n + 1)/6 for n = 9. 3. [Proof] Method A – Term-by-term residues 1² ≡ 1, 2² ≡ 4, 3² ≡ 9, 4² ≡ 6, 5² ≡ 5, 6² ≡ 6, 7² ≡ 9, 8² ≡ 4, 9² ≡ 1 (mod 10). Sum of residues: 1 + 4 + 9 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 + 4 + 1 = 45 ≡ 5 (mod 10). Hence the units digit is 5. Method B – Closed formula Σ_{k=1}^{9} k² = 9·10·19 / 6 = 285. Since 285 ≡ 5 (mod 10), the units digit is 5. 4. [Conclusion] Both direct residue addition and the sum-of-squares formula confirm the units digit of 1² + 2² + … + 9² is 5.
